04217nam a22004815i 9780804743648DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20221996cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047436487 a10.1515/97808047436482doi  a(DE-B1597)582193  a(OCoLC)1312726560  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aPOL0000002bisacsh1 aGuardino, Peter F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPeasants, Politics, and the Formation of Mexico's National State :bGuerrero, 1800-1857 /cPeter F. Guardino. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER 1 Society and Politics in Colonial Guerrero -- tCHAPTER 2 The War of Independence in Guerrero, 1808-1821 -- tCHAPTER 3 State Formation in Republican Guerrero, 1820-1840 -- tCHAPTER 4 National Politics and Local Social Movements in Guerrero, 1820-1840 -- tCHAPTER 5 Guerrero in the 1840s: Peasant Rebellions and Elite Politics -- tCHAPTER 6 The Revolution of Ayutla and La Reforma -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is a study of the important but little-understood role of peasants in the formation of the Mexican national state—from the end of the colonial era to the beginning of La Reforma, a moment in which liberalism became dominant in Mexican political culture. The book shows how Mexico's national political system was formed through local struggles and alliances that deeply involved elements of Mexico's impoverished rural masses, notably the peasants who took part in many of the local regional, and national rebellions that characterized early nineteenth-century politics. These rebellions were not battles over whether or not there was to be a state; they were contests over what the state was to be. The author focuses on the region of Guerrero, whose peasantry were deeply involved in the two most important broadly based revolts of the early nineteenth century: the War of Independence of 1810-21, and the 1853-55 Revolution of Ayutla, the rebellion that began La Reforma. The book's central contention is that there are fundamental links between state formation, elite politics, popular protest, and the construction of Mexico's modern political culture. Various elite groups advanced different models of the state, which in turn had different implications for, and impacts on, the lives of Mexico's lower classes. Contesting elites formed alliance with segments of Mexico's peasantry as well as the urban poor and these alliances were crucial in determining national political outcomes. Thus, the participation of wide sectors of the population in politics for varying reasons—and the subsequent learning of tactics and elaborations of discourse—left an enduring mark on Mexico's political system and culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aHistory -- World. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z97831107042110 cprintz978080472572940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080474364840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804743648423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804743648/original  a978-3-11-070421-1  Stanford University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles